{
  "doc_id": "41924",
  "text": "Our data indicate that during the Wasatchian (approx. 56-50 Ma) extensive regions of western North America were still fairly humid (blue and green colour code in figure 2) ; the first indication of less humid environments occurs in the southwest (figure 2a; see also table 1). During this time, high elevation (more than 3000 m, most probably accompanied by significant topographic relief) already characterized central British Columbia [CITATION_1] 15, [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , the Colorado Plateau region [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and the Sierra Nevada (e.g. [35] ), while the orogenic front was active in Idaho-Utah-Arizona (e.g. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] ).",
